args:
Recently, Leonidas, Chelle, and Phares came
together for a discussion. Leonidas and Chelle
eyed their brother with suspicion and
questioned his motives, but he brushed their
concerns aside and simply claimed that he
was going to forge his own path in life.
Recently, in the former capital Sol Alberia...
Well, well! If it isn't my dearest of all\nbrothers, Leonidas and Phares! What a\ncoincidence to find both of you here.

Since we're all together again, perhaps
we might sit down for a little tête-à-tête?
I can't imagine we'll have many such
opportunities in the future.
How unexpected. I thought you would\nreject the idea out of hand.
I have things I would ask of you both.\nThat is all there is to it.
Well, Sister? This meeting was your idea.\nWhat would you have us discuss?

What WON'T we discuss, my brother?!
For we certainly have a not-insubstantial
number of issues on our plate of late.
First of all, there is—
Why we've all sided with the Other?

Eee hee hee! Goodness me! I thought we
might dance around the issue or engage
in small talk first. But by all means,
let us discuss the dragon in the room.

Fine then. I'LL start. Leonidas, I never
imagined that you of all people would
bend the knee to any master. I'm DYING
to know what your endgame is in all this.
Then perhaps you should have those little\ncats you're so proud of suss it out.
Grumpiness does not become you, Brother.\nDo you have a tummy ache, perhaps?
What of you, Chelle? I find myself far\nmore curious in your own intentions.
Oh, I have many! But I am especially\nfascinated by the governance of\nthis new Empire.
Yes, it must be quite prolific to have some\ncalling it the ＂Evil Empire.＂

One of the roles of authority is the
redistribution of wealth—knowing how
much to gather from whom, and then
how to properly disperse it.

This has not changed under the Empire—
the ratio is merely different. To be frank,
I was quite surprised when I realized the
capital was in as good of a state as it is.
It IS rather peaceful for the capital\ncity of an ＂evil＂ empire.

And there's the rub. Morsayati takes much,
but that only increases what can be given
to those who stand to benefit. It is an
astoundingly normal political authority.
I found myself pondering if this was what\nwe could expect from a nation under the\ncontrol of the Other.
And yet in the countryside beyond the\ncapital, poverty and want runs rampant.
True. However, none of the citizens in the\ncapital seem particularly broken up over it.\nPerhaps that's just the nature of avarice.
Managing the desires of the smallfolk\nis another matter of importance for a\nleader of state.
And Zethia has a sterling reputation in the\ncapital—truly a most enviable position.
So that is your reason for\nsiding with Morsayati?
Who knows, Brother—though I DO love\nhearing the adoring praise of the masses.

Do not mock my growth, sir! I have seen
much and learned much in the recent past.
I'm certain that Leonidas here will confirm
my motives to be pure.
Ah, but you always were callous, Brother!\nIt reminds me of days gone by...
Whenever I approached the two of you\ntogether, you called me a nuisance\nand drove me hence.
Not that it ever stopped you.
Now that I think on it, when WAS the\nlast time the three of us spoke?
I believe our father was still with us.
And speaking of Father, I've a rather grim\nsuspicion I'd like to share with you.
Our father, as I recall, witnessed a shadow\nin the castle's Sacred Shard, and so sought\nout a new one to take its place, yes?
I heard as much. What of it?
Perhaps it is nothing. However, I'd never\nheard talk of shadows in Shards until\nFather's trip to the Binding Ruins.
Which makes you wonder why, of all the\nShards in all the land, the shadow\nappeared in the castle's Shard.

Indeed! That should have been the LAST
place such a thing would manifest—or at
the very least, one would expect it to
occur to the ones in Binding Ruins first.
Well, dear Phares? What do you think?
Because I believe that you will be the\nmost knowledgeable on the matter.
It's true that I've performed base research\non the Shards, but I fear I've learned\nnothing of particular note.
Unfortunate. I had rather hoped you would\nbe able to shed light on the situation.
My apologies for not living up\nto your expectations, Sister.
If the two of you don't stop this roundabout\ncleverness and just ask a straight question,\nI fear I may go mad.
Phares, what's going on in your head?\nSurely you're not planning to yield\nto Morsayati?
My thinking is precisely as I stated before.\nI've no interest in notions of good or evil.
All that matters is finding the path most\nefficacious for seeing my desires realized.
Revolution. Progress. Perhaps you\ncould even call it ＂creation.＂
One vague statement after the next.\nAre you trying to deceive us, my brother?
It is not my intention to do so. I merely\nstruggle with how best to convey my\nfeelings in mere words.
Then a more concrete question: What is\nyour plan for the immediate future?
For now, I think I might like to\nobtain the aid of my sibling.
Surely you must know what awaits you\nat the end of that path?
I make my own way. Nothing more.\nI would have you both do the same.
But perhaps, if the opportunity for our\npaths to converge once more arrives,\nwe might speak like this again.
